ualize diversity amid the dislocating forces of his day—mass immigration, orientalism, tourism, commercial publishing, and the international circulation of ethnographic objects—this book illuminates American art on the threshold of the twentieth-century "culture concept" promulgated by Franz Boas and other modern anthropologists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aArt. 4aHistory. 4aModern (late 19th Century to 1945). 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh1 aBraddock, Alan C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094386540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943865423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943865/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles